{
  "The SI unit of electric potential (voltage) is the:": "",
  "Coulomb": "",
  "Volt": "",
  "Ampere": "",
  "Ohm": "",
  "Electric potential is measured in volts (V). One volt equals one joule per coulomb: 1 V = 1 J/C.": "",
  "The electric potential at a distance r from a point charge Q is given by:": "",
  "V = kQ/r": "",
  "V = kQ/r²": "",
  "V = kQr": "",
  "V = kQ²/r": "",
  "The electric potential due to a point charge is V = kQ/r, which falls off as 1/r (not 1/r² like the electric field). It is a scalar quantity, not a vector.": "",
  "If a positive charge is released from rest in a uniform electric field, it will move toward:": "",
  "Higher potential": "",
  "Lower potential": "",
  "The same potential": "",
  "It will not move": "",
  "Positive charges naturally move from high to low potential (like a ball rolling downhill). Negative charges move from low to high potential.": "",
  "How much work is done in moving a 3 μC charge through a potential difference of 12 V?": "",
  "0.25 × 10⁻⁶ J": "",
  "36 J": "",
  "4 × 10⁻⁶ J": "",
  "36 × 10⁻⁶ J": "",
  "W = qΔV = 3 × 10⁻⁶ C × 12 V = 36 × 10⁻⁶ J = 36 μJ.": "",
  "Equipotential lines around a point charge are:": "",
  "Concentric circles (spheres in 3D) centered on the charge": "",
  "Straight lines radiating outward": "",
  "Random curved lines": "",
  "Parallel straight lines": "",
  "Since V = kQ/r depends only on distance r, all points at the same distance have the same potential. The equipotential surfaces are concentric spheres (circles in 2D).": "",
  "The relationship between electric field E and potential difference ΔV in a uniform field is:": "",
  "E = ΔV/d": "",
  "E = ΔV × d": "",
  "E = ΔV²/d": "",
  "E = d/ΔV": "",
  "In a uniform electric field, E = ΔV/d, where d is the distance along the field direction. The field points from high to low potential.": "",
  "Electric field lines and equipotential surfaces are always:": "",
  "Perpendicular to each other": "",
  "Parallel to each other": "",
  "At 45° to each other": "",
  "There is no fixed relationship": "",
  "Electric field lines are always perpendicular to equipotential surfaces. No work is done moving a charge along an equipotential, which requires the field to have zero component along it.": "",
  "The electric potential energy of two point charges q₁ and q₂ separated by distance r is:": "",
  "U = kq₁q₂r": "",
  "U = kq₁q₂/r": "",
  "U = kq₁q₂/r²": "",
  "U = kq₁q₂r²": "",
  "Electric potential energy U = kq₁q₂/r. If both charges have the same sign, U > 0 (repulsive). If opposite signs, U < 0 (attractive).": "",
  "An electron (q = −1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C) is accelerated through a potential difference of 100 V. What kinetic energy does it gain?": "",
  "100 J": "",
  "1 eV or 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ J": "",
  "10,000 eV": "",
  "100 eV or 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁷ J": "",
