  "At the surface of a charged conductor in electrostatic equilibrium, the electric potential is:": "",
  "Zero everywhere": "",
  "Different at different points": "",
  "Highest at sharp points": "",
  "The same everywhere on the surface": "",
  "A conductor's surface is an equipotential in electrostatic equilibrium. If it were not, there would be a tangential electric field that would move charges, contradicting equilibrium.": "",
  "What is 'electric potential'?": "",
  "The total charge on an object": "",
  "The electric potential energy per unit charge at a point in space: V = U/q": "",
  "The rate of flow of charge": "",
  "The force on a charge in an electric field": "",
  "Electric potential V is the potential energy per unit charge: V = U/q. It is a scalar field that describes the energy landscape for charges, measured in volts (J/C).": "",
  "What does 'potential difference' (voltage) mean?": "",
  "The difference in electric potential between two points, equal to the work per unit charge to move a charge between them": "",
  "The total charge stored in a battery, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "The current flowing through a wire, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The resistance of a circuit when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Potential difference (voltage) ΔV = V_B − V_A is the work done per unit charge to move a test charge from A to B: ΔV = W/q. It drives current in circuits.": "",
  "What is an 'equipotential surface'?": "",
  "A surface perpendicular to a current-carrying wire": "",
  "A surface where the electric field is zero": "",
  "A surface that produces equal amounts of positive and negative charge": "",
  "A surface on which every point has the same electric potential": "",
  "An equipotential surface connects all points at the same potential. No work is required to move a charge along an equipotential surface. These surfaces are always perpendicular to electric field lines.": "",
  "What is an 'electron-volt' (eV)?": "",
