  "The mass-energy of an electron according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The charge of one electron, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "The voltage required to stop an electron within the broader context of electron analysis": "",
  "An electron-volt is a unit of energy: 1 eV = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ J. It is the kinetic energy gained by a particle with charge e when accelerated through 1 V.": "",
  "What does 'electric potential energy' mean?": "",
  "The kinetic energy of a charged particle": "",
  "The energy dissipated by resistance": "",
  "The energy stored in a system of charges due to their positions relative to each other": "",
  "The power delivered by a battery": "",
  "Electric potential energy is the energy a system of charges possesses due to their arrangement. For two point charges, U = kq₁q₂/r. It converts to kinetic energy as charges move.": "",
  "What is a 'volt' defined as?": "",
  "One coulomb per second": "",
  "One joule per coulomb": "",
  "One watt per ampere": "",
  "One newton per ampere": "",
  "One volt = one joule per coulomb (1 V = 1 J/C). It represents the potential energy per unit charge.": "",
  "What does 'superposition of potentials' mean?": "",
  "Only the nearest charge determines the potential": "",
  "The total potential at a point is the algebraic (scalar) sum of potentials from each individual charge": "",
  "Potentials are always positive": "",
  "Potentials from different sources cancel out": "",
  "Unlike forces (vectors), potentials are scalars. The net potential at any point is simply the algebraic sum of the individual potentials from each charge: V_total = V₁ + V₂ + V₃ + ...": "",
  "What does 'grounding' mean in terms of potential?": "",
  "Making the object's charge equal to one coulomb": "",
  "Setting the potential of an object to its maximum value": "",
  "Connecting an object to the Earth, which is defined as the reference point at zero potential": "",
  "Removing all electric field from an object": "",
  "Grounding connects an object to the Earth, which serves as a reference at V = 0. Charge flows to or from ground until the object reaches zero potential.": "",
  "What is 'electric potential gradient'?": "",
  "The rate of change of electric potential with distance, related to the electric field: E = −dV/dx": "",
  "The rate at which charge flows through a circuit": "",
  "The maximum voltage a battery can produce": "",
  "The power dissipated in a resistor": "",
  "The electric potential gradient is how rapidly V changes with position. The electric field is the negative gradient of potential: E = −dV/dr. Steeper gradients mean stronger fields.": "",
  "What does 'conservative force' mean for the electric force?": "",
  "The force always points in the same direction": "",
  "The force conserves charge": "",
  "The work done by the force depends only on initial and final positions, not the path taken": "",
  "The force always does positive work": "",
  "The electric force is conservative: the work done moving a charge from A to B depends only on the endpoints, not the path. This allows us to define a potential energy function U(r).": "",
  "A defibrillator charges a capacitor to 5000 V and delivers approximately 200 J to a patient's chest. If the capacitor stores energy U = (1/2)CV², what is the approximate capacitance?": "",
  "160 μF": "",
  "0.16 μF": "",
  "16 μF": "",
  "1.6 μF": "",
  "C = 2U/V² = 2(200)/(5000)² = 400/25,000,000 = 1.6 × 10⁻⁵ F = 16 μF.": "",
  "In a television CRT, electrons are accelerated from rest through a potential difference of 25,000 V. What speed do they reach? (m_e = 9.11 × 10⁻³¹ kg, e = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C)": "",
  "About 9.4 × 10⁴ m/s": "",
  "About 4.7 × 10⁷ m/s": "",
  "About 3 × 10⁸ m/s": "",
  "About 9.4 × 10⁷ m/s": "",
  "KE = eV = (1/2)mv². v = sqrt(2eV/m) = sqrt(2 × 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ × 25000 / 9.11 × 10⁻³¹) = sqrt(8.79 × 10¹⁵) ≈ 9.4 × 10⁷ m/s (about 31% the speed of light).": "",
  "A 9 V battery is connected to a flashlight bulb. If 2 C of charge flows through the bulb, how much energy does the battery deliver?": "",
  "9 J": "",
  "18 J": "",
  "4.5 J": "",
  "2 J": "",
